y — use Eclipse for the Java code, and cmd just for Git commands.</h2><div class="font-claude-response relative leading-[1.65rem] [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:bg-bg-000/50 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Yes, exactly — use Eclipse for the Java code, and cmd just for Git commands. Here's the clean picture:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Eclipse</strong> → write and run your Java code
<strong>cmd</strong> → only for <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">git</code> commands (add, commit, push)</p>
<hr class="border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<h4 class="text-text-100 mt-2 -mb-1 text-base font-bold">Start from scratch in Eclipse:</h4>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="font-claude-response-body whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>File → New → Java Project</strong></li>
<li class="font-claude-response-body whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Name it <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">eticaret-sepeti</code></li>
<li class="font-claude-response-body whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Inside the project, find the <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">src</code> folder → right-click → <strong>New → Class</strong></li>
<li class="font-claude-response-body whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Name it <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">Main</code>, check "public static void main" → <strong>Finish</strong></li>
<li class="font-claude-response-body whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Paste your messy code in</li>
</ol>
<hr class="border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<h4 class="text-text-100 mt-2 -mb-1 text-base font-bold">Then link it to Git (in cmd):</h4>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Find where Eclipse saved your project. It's usually something like:</p>
