/span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Phase 3 — Observer</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Where</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token code-snippet code" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">`CartObserver.java`</span><span>, </span><span class="token token code-snippet code" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">`ConsoleObserver.java`</span><span>, updated </span><span class="token token code-snippet code" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">`ShoppingCart.java`</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Why</span><span>
</span></span><span>ShoppingCart had no way to notify other parts of the system when 
</span><span>something happened. Observer allows any number of listeners to react 
</span><span>to cart events without ShoppingCart knowing who is listening.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> What We Gained</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> Cart events (item added, discount applied) are now trackable
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> New observers can be added without touching ShoppingCart
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> Clean separation between event source and event handlers
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token hr" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">---</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">##</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Phase 3 — Strategy (completed)</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Where</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token code-snippet code" style="color: rgb(204, 123, 244);">`DiscountStrategy.java`</span><span> and all discount classes
</span></span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> Why</span><span>
</span></span><span>String-based discount selection was replaced with proper strategy 
</span><span>objects passed directly. Started in Phase 1, completed in Phase 3.
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222); font-weight: bold;">###</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(244, 123, 133); font-weight: bold;"> What We Gained</span><span>
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> No more string matching for discount selection
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> Discount behavior is fully encapsulated in each class
</span></span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(211, 215, 222);">-</span><span> Directly solves the OCP violation from PROBLEMS.md</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
